<TITLE> Hasina at Wazed Miah's bedside </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 7 (bdnews24.com) Prime minister Sheikh Hasina saw her ailing husband Dr M A Wazed Miah at Square Hospital on Thursday. She went there at 3:25pm, spent about half an hour at his bedside and left a few minutes before 4pm. Senior leaders of the ruling alliance headed by Awami League and one from the opposition thronged Square Hospital since Thursday morning to take a look at Dr Miah. Prof Sanawar Hossain, his physician, told reporters at noon his condition was 'a little better' Thursday though he was not yet out of danger. "Dr Miah's life-support system has been taken off. He is breathing normally now. We'll observe him closely through the next 24 hours," said Dr Hossain, director of medical services and consultant surgery, at the hospital. Security has been scaled up in the hospital neighbourhood as the prime minister was believed to visiting her husband any time. Until midday, local government minister Syed Ashraful Islam, parliamentary deputy leader Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury, the prime minister's health adviser professor Modasser Ali, Dhaka mayor and BNP leader Sadeque Hossain Khoka, Workers Party president Rashed Khan Menon were among those who visited the hospital to enquire into the wellbeing of Dr Miah. Hasina had also spent around an hour at the bedside of her husband on Wednesday. She was looking dejected as trudged out of the hospital corridor, helped by her sister, Rehana. Prof Hossain told bdnews24.com Dr Miah had been suffering for many years from a number of diseases including blood pressure, blood sugar, cardiac complications, a failed kidney and respiratory problems. Dr Miah, a nuclear scientists and former chief of Bangladesh Atomic Energy Commission, has been under treatment at Square Hospital for the last one year. Earlier, he received treatment in Delhi and Singapore also. In the most recent spell, Miah was admitted to the hospital on April 7, Hossain said. "His heart beat became irregular Wednesday morning. He was put on the pace machine eventually, as no medicine was working," he said. Recently, Dr Miah had an angioplasty at Singapore Mount Elizabeth Hospital. bd
